# wt.conf.example — every variable `wt` reads, with its real default.
#
# Copy to ~/.config/wt/config (or /etc/wt/config), or keep it in your project and point
# $WT_CONFIG at it. wt searches, in order:
#
#     $WT_CONFIG                     (a file path; WT_CONFIG= — empty — skips the file entirely)
#     $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/wt/config     (default ~/.config/wt/config)
#     /etc/wt/config
#
# The file is SOURCED as shell, so it may compute values. The ENVIRONMENT still wins over
# anything set here — that is how a one-off override (or a test) reaches in without editing the
# file. host-zfs-setup.sh reads this same file, the same way.
#
# A project usually keeps its config inside the checkout (so it is reviewed and versioned with
# the code) and maps it to /etc/wt/config in the dev image.

# ---- REQUIRED -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# There is no sensible default for these three; every dataset command dies without them.

# The checkout wt clones — the path as the process running wt sees it. A per-sandbox clone is
# mounted over exactly this path inside the sandbox's mount namespace, which is what keeps
# mtimes and absolute paths consistent and your build system warm.
#
# In a devcontainer this is the CONTAINER's path (/workspaces/myrepo), not the host's. When you
# run host-zfs-setup.sh on the host, pass the host path to it as an argument.
WT_CANONICAL=/workspaces/myrepo

# The ZFS dataset holding that checkout, and the dataset the per-sandbox clones hang under.
# Both are created by host-zfs-setup.sh. WT_DS_PARENT must not live under WT_DS_SRC: `wt gc`
# destroys children of WT_DS_PARENT, and inside WT_DS_SRC those children are your live data.
WT_DS_SRC=rpool/data/myrepo-src
WT_DS_PARENT=rpool/data/myrepo-wt

# ---- sandbox state ------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Where wt keeps trees/, meta/, active/ and locks/. It must be on the HOST side — outside every
# clone — or a sandbox's own bookkeeping would be inside the thing being destroyed. Point it at
# something backed by WT_DS_PARENT's mountpoint.
#
# Default: ${XDG_DATA_HOME:-$HOME/.local/share}/wt
#WT_HOME=$HOME/myrepo-wt

# ---- never-snapshotted subpaths -----------------------------------------------------------
# Space-separated subpaths, relative to WT_CANONICAL, that must NEVER be captured in a snapshot
# — huge, churny, or shared-by-design directories (logs, datasets, caches you want to stay
# common across sandboxes).
#
# The mechanism: host-zfs-setup.sh makes each entry its own ZFS child dataset
# ($WT_DS_SRC/<sub>). `wt new` snapshots WT_DS_SRC NON-recursively, so a child dataset is simply
# not in the snapshot — and therefore not in the clone, where it appears as an empty mountpoint
# directory. wt-setup.sh then bind-mounts the canonical copy back over that empty directory, so
# every sandbox sees ONE live shared copy on the host, and no sandbox pays to duplicate it.
#
# Consequences worth knowing before you add one:
#   * it is shared, not copied — a sandbox writing there writes the real thing, for everyone;
#   * changing this list later means running host-zfs-setup.sh again (it will move an existing
#     directory's content into the new child dataset for you);
#   * use TOP-LEVEL directories. A nested entry (build/logs) would force build/ to be a dataset
#     too, and then everything under build/ — not just build/logs — would be absent from every
#     sandbox. host-zfs-setup.sh refuses to do that silently.
#
# Default: empty (nothing excluded).
#WT_SNAPSHOT_EXCLUDE=logs

# ---- identity -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The unprivileged user a sandbox command runs as. wt needs root only to mount the clone, never
# to run your shell.
#
# PIN these if wt is ever invoked as root — `wt ssh-serve` is, over `docker exec -u0`, and the
# defaults would then compute a target uid of 0. The uid is also what host-zfs-setup.sh
# delegates the ZFS permissions to, and it must match on both sides of the container boundary
# (bind mounts preserve uids, not names).
#
# Defaults: $(id -u) / $(id -g) / the name of that uid.
#WT_TARGET_UID=1000
#WT_TARGET_GID=1000
#WT_TARGET_USER=dev

# ---- provenance ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ZFS user property stamped on every snapshot wt takes. `wt gc` and `wt list` reap ONLY snapshots
# that carry it, so a hand-made @wt-* snapshot is never destroyed on the strength of its name.
# Changing it later strands existing snapshots as "untagged": they stop being gc's business and
# have to be reaped by hand.
#
# Default: com.wt:managed
#WT_ZFS_PROP=com.wt:managed

# ---- namespace hold paths -----------------------------------------------------------------
# Bind targets, inside the sandbox's mount namespace, that keep main's live .git and each
# WT_SNAPSHOT_EXCLUDE subpath reachable after the clone is mounted over WT_CANONICAL. You only
# need to set these to namespace them against another wt install on the same host.
#
# Defaults: /tmp/wt-git-main and /tmp/wt-holds
#WT_GIT_HOLD=/tmp/myrepo-git-main
#WT_HOLD_DIR=/tmp/myrepo-wt-holds

# ---- session hooks ------------------------------------------------------------------------
# wt ships with NO hooks and has no opinion about what a sandbox should run — no language, no
# toolchain, no daemon, no cache. Everything project-specific happens here. Each is a COMMAND
# STRING, run with `bash -c`, so it can be a script plus arguments.
#
# WT_HOOK_ENTER — runs INSIDE the sandbox namespace, as WT_TARGET_UID, once per `wt enter`,
#   after the mounts are up and before your command is exec'd.
#     env in : WT_SANDBOX (the sandbox name), WT_CANONICAL (here: this sandbox's clone),
#              WT_SRC_CLONE, WT_META, WT_SNAPSHOT_EXCLUDE, WT_SRC_COMMIT, WT_REF_SHA.
#     stdout : every well-formed KEY=VALUE line is exported into the session (direnv-style).
#              stdout is therefore precious — redirect everything else to stderr or /dev/null.
#     exit   : ran-then-failed is tolerated (the env it already printed still applies, so print
#              env FIRST, before anything that can fail). Could-not-be-executed (126/127) ABORTS
#              the session — a hook that silently doesn't run means the session quietly loses
#              everything the hook guarantees, which is worse than not starting.
#
# WT_HOOK_TEARDOWN — runs HOST-side when a sandbox's resources must be released: the LAST
#   session exiting, `wt rm`, and `wt gc` reaping an orphan.
#     env in : WT_SANDBOX. Nothing else is guaranteed — `export` anything else it needs.
#     exit   : ignored. Must be idempotent: it is called when nothing is running, and possibly
#              more than once.
#   It is not optional bookkeeping. Anything the enter hook left running in the namespace (a
#   build daemon, a language server) pins the clone's mount and would otherwise block
#   `zfs destroy`, so `wt rm` would fail on a sandbox that merely looks idle.
#
# A hook that gives each sandbox its own build-cache daemon instead of a shared one:
#
#     #!/bin/bash
#     case "$1" in
#       enter)
#         echo "MYCACHE_SOCK=/tmp/mycache-$WT_SANDBOX.sock"     # session env, printed FIRST
#         MYCACHE_SOCK=/tmp/mycache-$WT_SANDBOX.sock mycache start >/dev/null 2>&1 || true
#         ;;
#       teardown)
#         MYCACHE_SOCK=/tmp/mycache-$WT_SANDBOX.sock mycache stop >/dev/null 2>&1 || true
#         ;;
#     esac
#
# Defaults: both empty (no hooks).
#WT_HOOK_ENTER='/workspaces/myrepo/.devcontainer/wt-hook enter'
#WT_HOOK_TEARDOWN='/workspaces/myrepo/.devcontainer/wt-hook teardown'

# ---- optional ssh transport (only if you use wt-ssh) --------------------------------------
# `wt-ssh` runs on your LOCAL machine and proxies an ssh session into a sandbox over
# `docker exec` — no listening port. Core wt never calls docker; skip this whole section if you
# do not use it.
#
# Because wt-ssh runs on the host, it cannot read the container's /etc/wt/config: it looks for
# <checkout>/.wt.conf, then <checkout>/.config/wt.conf (override with $WT_SSH_CONFIG). Keeping
# the config in the repo is what lets one file serve both sides.

# Generated sshd config + authorized_keys, written by `wt ssh-setup` (inside the container).
# Default: $HOME/.wt-ssh
#WT_SSH_DIR=$HOME/.wt-ssh

# Path to wt-ssh on your LOCAL machine, relative to the checkout — baked into the ProxyCommand
# lines that `wt ssh-config` prints for your ~/.ssh/config.
# Default: .wt/wt-ssh
#WT_SSH_PROXY=.devcontainer/worktree/wt-ssh

# Where wt is installed INSIDE the container (see install.sh). Used as the sshd ForceCommand and
# by wt-ssh's `docker exec`.
# Default: /usr/local/bin/wt
#WT_REMOTE_BIN=/usr/local/bin/wt

# ---- test seam ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Not config: wt-setup.sh's privilege drop is a single overridable command (WT_DROP_PRIV), so an
# unprivileged unit test can substitute a no-op. Setting it in a config file is a way to get
# your sandboxes running as root by accident. Don't.
